WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.560 --> 00:00:02.569
It's 1924.

00:00:02.569 --> 00:00:06.072
You're taking your family 
on a weekend&nbsp;trip to the big city. &nbsp;

00:00:06.072 --> 00:00:08.108
For every generation before&nbsp;you

00:00:08.108 --> 00:00:10.128
this would have been a difficult train&nbsp;journey

00:00:10.128 --> 00:00:12.989
or a multi-day journey by horse. &nbsp;

00:00:12.989 --> 00:00:14.163
But&nbsp;not for you

00:00:14.163 --> 00:00:16.825
because you just bought a car.&nbsp;

00:00:16.825 --> 00:00:20.957
Suddenly, you could travel anywhere at any&nbsp;time.

00:00:20.957 --> 00:00:22.756
It was the ultimate freedom, &nbsp;

00:00:22.756 --> 00:00:26.240
and&nbsp;car ownership took off around the world.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:28.264
But all of this was only possible 

00:00:28.264 --> 00:00:31.033
because&nbsp;cars had just become affordable. 

00:00:31.033 --> 00:00:32.862
Well,&nbsp;one car did.&nbsp;

00:00:32.862 --> 00:00:35.101
 The Ford Model T. 

00:00:35.101 --> 00:00:36.986
When it launched in&nbsp;1908&nbsp;

00:00:36.986 --> 00:00:42.483
it cost just $850, around $30,000 in today's&nbsp;money.

00:00:42.483 --> 00:00:46.072
But just a few years later, that price was&nbsp;cut in half &nbsp;

00:00:46.072 --> 00:00:52.005
and by 1924, it had fallen all the way to just $260.&nbsp;

00:00:52.005 --> 00:00:56.111
But the Ford Model T was by&nbsp;no means a special car. 

00:00:56.111 --> 00:00:59.866
The real breakthrough&nbsp;was the factory it was made in.

00:00:59.866 --> 00:01:02.921
This place was&nbsp;an efficiency machine. 

00:01:02.921 --> 00:01:05.255
Raw materials came into&nbsp;the factory 

00:01:05.255 --> 00:01:07.524
and finished cars left. &nbsp;

00:01:07.524 --> 00:01:11.120
Instead of&nbsp;cars being 
carefully handcrafted on a workbench,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:15.239
a constant flow of chassis 
moved through the&nbsp;factory 24/7 &nbsp;

00:01:15.239 --> 00:01:17.760
and parts were added continuously.&nbsp;

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:21.580
This genius idea took the 
total assembly time&nbsp;from 12 hours 

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:24.153
down to just 90 minutes

00:01:24.153 --> 00:01:27.907
with a&nbsp;new car leaving the factory every 40 seconds.&nbsp;

00:01:27.907 --> 00:01:30.742
We modeled the entire thing in great detail 

00:01:30.742 --> 00:01:34.222
to show you the genius 
design of the Ford Model T&nbsp;factory &nbsp;

00:01:34.222 --> 00:01:38.590
and the incredible engineering 
that went&nbsp;into mastering mass production.

00:01:38.590 --> 00:01:42.398
To understand just&nbsp;how 
monumental Ford's impact was

00:01:42.398 --> 00:01:45.832
we need to look&nbsp;at car factories before the Model T.&nbsp;

00:01:45.832 --> 00:01:51.100
Normally cars&nbsp;would be assembled 
on a stand by a team of skilled craftsmen.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:53.351
Almost nothing was automated 

00:01:53.351 --> 00:01:58.894
and a&nbsp;lot of time was spent simply walking around the&nbsp;factory and bringing parts to the car. &nbsp;

00:01:58.894 --> 00:02:00.567
Any delay&nbsp;in a single task 

00:02:00.567 --> 00:02:04.116
meant that the other 
workers had&nbsp;to wait to do their task. 

00:02:04.116 --> 00:02:06.831
The whole process was&nbsp;slow and expensive, 

00:02:06.831 --> 00:02:08.981
and a typical car company like Cadillac&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.981 --> 00:02:12.257
could only make around 2,000 cars&nbsp;each year. &nbsp;

00:02:12.257 --> 00:02:14.480
To make cars affordable for the masses

00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:17.662
they'd have to be produced in enormous quantities.&nbsp;

00:02:17.662 --> 00:02:21.325
And no one understood this 
more than the Ford&nbsp;Motor Company.

00:02:21.325 --> 00:02:26.562
Henry Ford himself often gets&nbsp;credit 
for turning his factory into an assembly&nbsp;line

00:02:26.562 --> 00:02:32.181
But in reality, the idea came from 
one of&nbsp;Ford's production engineers, William Clan. 

00:02:32.181 --> 00:02:34.308
At the&nbsp;start of 1913&nbsp;

00:02:34.308 --> 00:02:36.863
he visited a meat packing factory&nbsp;in Chicago

00:02:36.863 --> 00:02:40.756
which was known to be one of 
the most&nbsp;efficient factories in the country.&nbsp;

00:02:40.756 --> 00:02:44.215
When he was&nbsp;there, he was amazed by what he saw. 

00:02:44.215 --> 00:02:46.572
The animals&nbsp;were hung from a rail on a ceiling

00:02:46.572 --> 00:02:49.245
and moved to&nbsp;various stations around the factory 

00:02:49.245 --> 00:02:50.276
where they&nbsp;were cut up, &nbsp;

00:02:50.276 --> 00:02:50.958
processed, 

00:02:50.958 --> 00:02:53.439
and packaged, ready to be&nbsp;shipped out. 

00:02:53.439 --> 00:02:57.332
The whole process was 
simplified down&nbsp;to the most basic tasks

00:02:57.332 --> 00:02:59.867
 and spread across multiple&nbsp;workers. 

00:02:59.867 --> 00:03:01.949
This gave William an idea.

00:03:01.949 --> 00:03:05.000
 Although&nbsp;this process 
worked for taking apart an animal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.400
perhaps it could work for putting together a car.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:10.092
He took the idea to Ford 

00:03:10.092 --> 00:03:13.920
and they immediately&nbsp;began 
testing it out on a relatively simple part,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:15.713
the flywheel magneto. 

00:03:15.713 --> 00:03:21.862
Normally, a team of 30&nbsp;workers would each 
assemble entire magnetos at&nbsp;individual workbenches. &nbsp;

00:03:21.862 --> 00:03:26.238
With this setup, around&nbsp;
800 magnetos could be made per day. 

00:03:26.238 --> 00:03:27.839
Ford got&nbsp;rid of the workbenches&nbsp;

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:30.783
 and installed a single long&nbsp;steel table. 

00:03:30.783 --> 00:03:33.254
The workers were arranged in specific positions &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.254 --> 00:03:36.086
and instead of assembling a complete&nbsp;magneto, 

00:03:36.086 --> 00:03:38.351
they were told to only perform a single&nbsp;task &nbsp;

00:03:38.351 --> 00:03:40.919
and slide the magneto onto the next person.&nbsp;

00:03:40.919 --> 00:03:44.032
Since each worker was just repeating the same&nbsp;task, 

00:03:44.032 --> 00:03:49.106
it brought the total assembly time 
down from&nbsp;20 minutes to just 13 minutes. 

00:03:49.106 --> 00:03:51.233
To speed up the&nbsp;process even more

00:03:51.233 --> 00:03:55.760
Ford replaced the table with&nbsp;a 
conveyor belt that moved at a constant speed.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.760 --> 00:03:58.118
This caused the slow workers to speed up 

00:03:58.118 --> 00:04:00.000
and the&nbsp;fastest workers to slow down, 

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.457
balancing out the&nbsp;line and keeping everything in sync. 

00:04:03.457 --> 00:04:05.000
In just a&nbsp;few months, 

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.632
Ford went from producing 800 Magnetos&nbsp;a day

00:04:07.632 --> 00:04:10.147
to almost 3,000. 

00:04:10.147 --> 00:04:12.481
This way of working was&nbsp;so successful &nbsp;

00:04:12.481 --> 00:04:17.176
that Ford immediately began 
trying&nbsp;to use it for more complex parts.

00:04:17.176 --> 00:04:18.724
The engine, for&nbsp;example&nbsp;

00:04:18.724 --> 00:04:24.404
took around 10 hours to produce and 
had&nbsp;to travel over 1,200 m around the factory

00:04:24.404 --> 00:04:27.358
 as it&nbsp;moved from one machine to another.

00:04:27.358 --> 00:04:30.517
 Ford knew that&nbsp;arranging 
these machines in a more logical order&nbsp;

00:04:30.517 --> 00:04:32.626
would massively speed things up. 

00:04:32.626 --> 00:04:33.520
But at the time

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:35.668
this was simply impossible. 

00:04:35.668 --> 00:04:38.241
Most factories were&nbsp;mechanically powered&nbsp;

00:04:38.241 --> 00:04:40.873
meaning a large drive shaft&nbsp;at the center of the factory

00:04:40.873 --> 00:04:45.340
provided turning&nbsp;power to the machines 
through a complex system&nbsp;of pulleys.

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:49.301
Since each machine required a 
specific&nbsp;amount of speed and power 

00:04:49.301 --> 00:04:53.125
they had to be placed&nbsp;near a pulley 
that was geared to that specific&nbsp;speed.&nbsp;

00:04:53.125 --> 00:04:56.507
 The result was that heavy machinery&nbsp;
ended up on one side of the factory &nbsp;

00:04:56.507 --> 00:04:59.760
and more&nbsp;lightweight machines 
ended up on the other side.

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:01.979
It was completely unoptimized

00:05:01.979 --> 00:05:07.211
and workers wasted a&nbsp;lot of time simply moving 
parts around the factory&nbsp;from machine to machine. 

00:05:07.211 --> 00:05:08.322
To get around this

00:05:08.322 --> 00:05:11.737
Ford&nbsp;decided to make the entire factory electric &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.737 --> 00:05:14.459
and set up an enormous power station at the factory

00:05:14.459 --> 00:05:17.503
which produced 34 megawatts of electricity. 

00:05:17.503 --> 00:05:20.000
With&nbsp;this, Ford could get rid of the heavy, 

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:21.165
dangerous&nbsp;drive shafts 

00:05:21.165 --> 00:05:25.149
and simply run cables 
to power each machine individually. &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.149 --> 00:05:28.124
With no restrictions&nbsp;on 
where the machinery could be placed

00:05:28.124 --> 00:05:30.646
Ford&nbsp;rearranged the engine assembly line,&nbsp;

00:05:30.646 --> 00:05:36.460
and the total&nbsp;travel distance 
was reduced from 1,200 m to just&nbsp;90.&nbsp;

00:05:36.460 --> 00:05:38.407
Throughout 1913

00:05:38.407 --> 00:05:40.000
Ford went crazy

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:41.761
creating new&nbsp;assembly lines, 

00:05:41.761 --> 00:05:44.000
installing custom-made machines,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.615
and simplifying jobs down to their most basic&nbsp;tasks. 

00:05:47.615 --> 00:05:51.151
The radiator, which was 
made up of 95 thin&nbsp;metal tubes, 

00:05:51.151 --> 00:05:54.602
had to be fitted and hand soldered&nbsp;
by a skilled worker. 

00:05:54.602 --> 00:05:57.142
Ford built a machine that&nbsp;arranged the metal tubes 

00:05:57.142 --> 00:06:00.560
and passed them through&nbsp;a 
furnace to do the soldering automatically.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:03.160
Parts that had to be machined on a lathe first&nbsp;

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:05.155
required the workers to screw the part into&nbsp;place

00:06:05.155 --> 00:06:07.558
 and unscrew it when it was finished. 

00:06:07.558 --> 00:06:10.400
Ford&nbsp;redesigned the lathe to have an automatic clamp,&nbsp;

00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:14.887
which reduced the 
duration of each task by more&nbsp;than 90%

00:06:14.887 --> 00:06:16.560
Thanks to all of this optimization,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:23.935
the total amount of man-hour to produce&nbsp;
a single car went from 450 hours to just&nbsp;150 hours.

00:06:23.935 --> 00:06:27.920
But there was at least one&nbsp;
downside to this new way of working.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:30.619
The work had become so monotonous for the workers&nbsp;

00:06:30.619 --> 00:06:33.640
that more and more people started to quit. 

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:35.699
New&nbsp;workers were constantly having to be hired&nbsp;

00:06:35.699 --> 00:06:37.402
 and&nbsp;trained into the role 

00:06:37.402 --> 00:06:40.561
which started to hurt the&nbsp;
overall efficiency of the factory.

00:06:40.561 --> 00:06:46.030
Henry Ford&nbsp;saw this and decided to do 
something that would&nbsp;be unimaginable today. &nbsp;

00:06:46.030 --> 00:06:52.831
He announced that Ford&nbsp;would raise 
the daily salary for all workers from&nbsp;$2.34 to $5&nbsp;

00:06:52.831 --> 00:06:56.428
and shorten the workday from 9 hours&nbsp;to 8 hours. 

00:06:56.428 --> 00:07:00.308
More than 10,000 people 
turned up the&nbsp;next day to apply for a job. 

00:07:00.308 --> 00:07:03.665
And Ford never had&nbsp;trouble losing workers again. 

00:07:03.665 --> 00:07:06.778
This was headline&nbsp;news all over the country, &nbsp;

00:07:06.778 --> 00:07:09.871
and it was hard to see&nbsp;it 
as anything other than a positive. 

00:07:09.871 --> 00:07:10.880
Nowadays,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:16.162
it's easy to imagine how a story like this&nbsp;
can be sensationalized and manipulated by the&nbsp;media.

00:07:16.162 --> 00:07:19.630
That's why I'm happy that 
