Again, it's ground.news/primal&nbsp;to see the full picture.

00:08:44.764 --> 00:08:47.840
In order&nbsp;to make the Model T available to the masses,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:49.855
Ford had spent the entire year 

00:08:49.855 --> 00:08:53.712
rearranging&nbsp;machinery and 
setting up assembly lines with&nbsp;one goal

00:08:53.712 --> 00:08:56.209
make as many cars as possible. 

00:08:56.209 --> 00:08:59.120
All of&nbsp;the fixed costs, like the factory and machines,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:02.384
stayed basically the same 
no matter how many cars&nbsp;they produced

00:09:02.384 --> 00:09:03.920
and so the more cars they made,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:05.990
the cheaper would be per car.

00:09:05.990 --> 00:09:07.852
It may seem&nbsp;obvious now, 

00:09:07.852 --> 00:09:10.505
but at the time, none of this had&nbsp;been figured out&nbsp;

00:09:10.505 --> 00:09:14.476
and Ford was really pioneering&nbsp;
the idea of mass production.

00:09:14.476 --> 00:09:15.920
 By the end of 1913,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.920 --> 00:09:18.427
Ford had more than doubled its daily output 

00:09:18.427 --> 00:09:22.559
and&nbsp;the price of a Model T 
had dropped by almost&nbsp;$200.&nbsp;

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:26.693
 But although Ford had optimized 
the assembly&nbsp;of thousands of parts, 

00:09:26.693 --> 00:09:30.521
the final cars were still being 
assembled at stationary workbenches&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.521 --> 00:09:34.357
and&nbsp;this quickly became 
the bottleneck for the entire&nbsp;production. &nbsp;

00:09:34.357 --> 00:09:36.433
And so in 1914, 

00:09:36.433 --> 00:09:39.717
Ford set up the holy&nbsp;grail of factory efficiency,

00:09:39.717 --> 00:09:41.890
 the final assembly&nbsp;line. &nbsp;

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:43.155
The idea was simple. 

00:09:43.155 --> 00:09:44.513
All of the sub-assembly&nbsp;
lines 

00:09:44.513 --> 00:09:48.933
would feed a constant supply of 
finished&nbsp;parts into the final assembly line 

00:09:48.933 --> 00:09:52.575
where they&nbsp;would be mounted onto 
the chassis as it moved through the factory. &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:52.575 --> 00:09:54.266
The entire assembly process&nbsp;was studied 

00:09:54.266 --> 00:09:57.723
and broken down into 45 individual&nbsp;steps &nbsp;

00:09:57.723 --> 00:10:01.960
assigned to 140 workers 
and spread out&nbsp;across the line. 

00:10:01.960 --> 00:10:03.456
Here's how it worked. 

00:10:03.456 --> 00:10:06.340
Basic&nbsp;chassis would leave a sub-assembly line 

00:10:06.340 --> 00:10:12.065
and enter&nbsp;the start of the final assembly line where they&nbsp;would get pulled along by a chain driven sled.&nbsp;

00:10:12.065 --> 00:10:13.918
As&nbsp;the chassis moved down the line, 

00:10:13.918 --> 00:10:15.862
workers added the&nbsp;front and rear axles 

00:10:15.862 --> 00:10:17.251
and soon after the gas tanks,&nbsp;

00:10:17.251 --> 00:10:21.602
which were conveniently rolled 
down a chute from a&nbsp;sub-assembly line above.

00:10:21.602 --> 00:10:22.760
Further down the line,&nbsp;

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:25.580
the engine would be dropped 
into place from an overhead rail &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:25.580 --> 00:10:29.231
that fed the workers with a constant&nbsp;
supply of finished engines. 

00:10:29.231 --> 00:10:30.400
The dashboard,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:32.321
steering, exhaust, and pedals

00:10:32.321 --> 00:10:35.000
would all come&nbsp;together in a quick sequence of tasks. 

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.731
Finished&nbsp;wheels from the sub-assembly line &nbsp;

00:10:37.731 --> 00:10:39.516
would drop down&nbsp;holes in the floor, 

00:10:39.516 --> 00:10:42.767
and two workers would 
attach&nbsp;all four wheels to the car. 

00:10:42.767 --> 00:10:45.918
The radiators were&nbsp;stored in a raised platform above 

00:10:45.918 --> 00:10:47.289
and would slide down a chute,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:47.289 --> 00:10:49.500
 ready for the workers to install.&nbsp;

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:52.480
For work that had to be done underneath the car,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:56.362
special creepers were made that 
could clamp onto&nbsp;the chassis as it moved. 

00:10:56.362 --> 00:10:58.150
This meant that workers could lie down&nbsp;

00:10:58.150 --> 00:11:02.280
 and work on the car with 
both hands&nbsp;as they got pulled along. 

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:05.737
After 44 steps, the cars 
would be driven off the assembly line &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:05.737 --> 00:11:10.129
under their&nbsp;own power onto another 
assembly line outside the&nbsp;factory. &nbsp;

00:11:10.129 --> 00:11:13.675
Just above the final assembly line was the body shop.

00:11:13.675 --> 00:11:16.030
 Here, all of the body parts were&nbsp;&nbsp; stamped 

00:11:16.030 --> 00:11:20.358
and assembled into a lightweight 
piece and&nbsp;moved outside to a platform. 

00:11:20.358 --> 00:11:23.434
The finished chassis&nbsp;would move under this platform

00:11:23.434 --> 00:11:25.675
and the body would&nbsp;be lowered on top, 

00:11:25.675 --> 00:11:29.595
completing the entire assembly&nbsp;in just 90 minutes. &nbsp;

00:11:29.595 --> 00:11:33.952
By the end of 1914, Ford had&nbsp;
set up three identical assembly lines 

00:11:33.952 --> 00:11:40.000
to raise its&nbsp;daily output from 450 
to well over 1,000 cars a&nbsp;day. &nbsp;

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.993
This increase in production allowed Ford 
to&nbsp;drop the price of its touring model &nbsp;

00:11:43.993 --> 00:11:48.326
to just $345&nbsp;by 1916. 

00:11:48.326 --> 00:11:50.912
But no matter how efficient the factory became, &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:50.912 --> 00:11:53.978
there was still one huge bottleneck.&nbsp;

00:11:53.978 --> 00:11:57.600
Although the overall labor costs per car were low,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.600 --> 00:12:00.944
most of the cost per car went into buying&nbsp;materials

00:12:00.944 --> 00:12:03.534
which were still being purchased&nbsp;externally. &nbsp;

00:12:03.534 --> 00:12:07.037
Ford realized that if it could control&nbsp;
the production of every part,

00:12:07.037 --> 00:12:10.104
 right down to&nbsp;pulling the material out of the ground, 

00:12:10.104 --> 00:12:12.236
it would&nbsp;save enormously on costs 

00:12:12.236 --> 00:12:15.280
and guarantee a constant&nbsp;supply of parts. &nbsp;

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:18.441
Ford purchased iron ore mines 
in&nbsp;Michigan and Minnesota, 

00:12:18.441 --> 00:12:20.000
coal mines in Kentucky,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.883
forests for wood, and its own railroad. 

00:12:22.883 --> 00:12:26.442
Ore from&nbsp;the mines was delivered
 into the factory using its&nbsp;own trains, &nbsp;

00:12:26.442 --> 00:12:31.244
where it was transformed into steel&nbsp;
using furnaces powered by its own coal. 

00:12:31.244 --> 00:12:33.239
In just&nbsp;a handful of years, 

00:12:33.239 --> 00:12:39.033
Ford had taken complete&nbsp;control of 
basically every material needed to make the Model T, &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.033 --> 00:12:45.840
and it brought the total&nbsp;material 
cost per car from $590 to just $190.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:49.704
Ford had mastered the art of mass production. 

00:12:49.704 --> 00:12:53.280
Year&nbsp;after year, it kept producing more and more cars,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:55.874
finally reaching a peak in 1923 

00:12:55.874 --> 00:13:02.105
when it produced&nbsp;more than 2 million 
and its price dropped to just $260. &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:02.105 --> 00:13:06.133
By this point, almost everything
 inside the&nbsp;factory had been optimized. 

00:13:06.133 --> 00:13:09.067
But Henry Ford had&nbsp;one last idea,

00:13:09.067 --> 00:13:13.528
 an idea that was so significant, 
it&nbsp;still benefits us to this day. 

00:13:13.528 --> 00:13:15.495
He recognized that&nbsp;the health of his workers

00:13:15.495 --> 00:13:19.199
made a difference in the&nbsp;
overall quality and output of work. &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:19.199 --> 00:13:21.212
Someone that was well-rested and refreshed

00:13:21.212 --> 00:13:23.600
 would come to work&nbsp;and do a better job. 

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:29.050
At the time, normal factory&nbsp;jobs 
still required long 10 to 15 hour shifts&nbsp;

00:13:29.050 --> 00:13:31.725
&nbsp;with only a single day off on Sundays. 

00:13:31.725 --> 00:13:33.096
To give his workers more rest time&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.096 --> 00:13:36.261
 and to ensure that&nbsp;they came to work more refreshed, 

00:13:36.261 --> 00:13:38.916
he introduced the 5-day work week. &nbsp;

00:13:38.916 --> 00:13:41.502
Workers would now make $6 per&nbsp;day, 

00:13:41.502 --> 00:13:45.234
but only work 40 hours a week 
and have 2 days&nbsp;off at the end. 

00:13:45.234 --> 00:13:47.738
He literally invented the weekend&nbsp;

00:13:47.738 --> 00:13:49.417
and it worked. 

00:13:49.417 --> 00:13:52.346
Ford saw a noticeable increase in&nbsp;productivity &nbsp;

00:13:52.346 --> 00:13:56.557
and after this almost all industries&nbsp;
adopted this working schedule 

00:13:56.557 --> 00:13:59.280
and it's why we&nbsp;still have it today. &nbsp;

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:04.640
It's hard to overstate just&nbsp;how impactful 
Ford's ideas were on our society.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:07.327
Today, almost every manufactured product 

00:14:07.327 --> 00:14:10.679
like TVs,&nbsp;phones, refrigerators, and washing machines 

00:14:10.679 --> 00:14:13.881
are&nbsp;only available in large quantities and at low&nbsp;prices 

00:14:13.881 --> 00:14:18.530
because of the incredible engineering
that happened inside this factory. &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:18.530 --> 00:14:20.805
Thanks for&nbsp;watching, and I'll see you in the next video.

